The core implementation is now pinned down. I’ve verified there is no `MATCH`-side `LIMIT`, the scorer does use the passed `weights`/`b`/`k1`, and the write/migration paths are safe on malformed JSON; the remaining question is whether the scorer’s Rust tokenization is faithful enough to the FTS5 tokenizer it relies on for recall.
codex
## Verdict: CONCERN

### 1. [medium] BM25F scoring is not tokenization-faithful to the FTS5 index it ranks
Refs: [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10278), [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10303), [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10347), [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10425), [schema lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:430)

`search_index_v2` recalls with `porter unicode61 remove_diacritics 2`, but the in-engine scorer recomputes tf/df/field lengths with a simpler lowercase alnum splitter. That means porter/diacritic matches can be recalled by `MATCH` yet scored as if the term were absent or rarer than it is, so ranking is wrong for stemmed/diacritic variants even though recall is intact. The BM25F formula and live `weights`/`b`/`k1` plumbing are otherwise sound; the issue is that the scorer is not measuring terms under the same tokenization semantics as the index it depends on.

### 2. [low] `search_index_v2.status` does not currently match shipped G10 search-filter status semantics
Refs: [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1492), [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4951), [schema lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:436), [engine lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.14-slice-10-20260704T002826Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10254)

Step 17 and the synchronous write path safely derive `status` from `$.status` under `json_valid`, so malformed or missing JSON does not abort migration or writes. But shipped G10 search filtering still reads vec0 `status`, and that metadata is still hardwired to the empty-string sentinel today. The implementation comments claiming this is “the same status the G10 SearchFilter reads” are therefore inaccurate in the current tree.

## What passed on inspection
- The load-bearing deviation is bounded: candidate recall still comes from `search_index_v2 MATCH`, and there is no `ORDER BY`/`LIMIT` on that candidate pull before BM25F scoring, so there is no top-k omission risk from truncating recalled candidates.
- The BM25F math shape is standard: per-field weighted normalized tf, Robertson-style idf, one saturation with live `k1`, and live `b` in the field-length normalization. `weights`, `b`, and `k1` are genuine parameters, not dead config.
- `r_f5_1_field_weight_flips_ranking_vs_body_only_baseline` is non-vacuous. It is structurally capable of failing if field weights are ignored because the gold hit exists only in `kind` and the distractor only in `body`; the asserted order flip depends on weighting.
- Step 17 is contiguous and forward-only: `SCHEMA_VERSION` is 17, the registry head is step 17, and migration application still enforces `step_id == current + 1`.
- `search_index` is retained; `search_index_v2` is additive. The write path populates v2 synchronously in the same transaction via the Slice-5 D2 seam, and the determinism test now serializes `search_index_v2` as part of the comparison surface.
- I found no embedder/pooling/quant/vector-partition changes in the slice code under review; D6 holds from the code inspected here.

## Reviewer process notes
